                                <p>In short, a disruptive technology is something that transforms a historically expensive product, which only a few people with a lot of money and a lot of skill have access to, by making it more affordable and available to a wider group of people.</p>
                                <p>The term was first brought to public attention in 1995 by a Harvard Professor named <a href="https://hbr.org/2015/12/what-is-disruptive-innovation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Clayton M. Christensen</a>.</p>
                                <p>This level of innovation is usually so huge that it completely eradicates the previous incumbent (in some cases very quickly). The reasons behind this usually being that the technology offers exponentially better performance, while being produced at a markedly lower cost. Before you know it the new technology is everywhere!</p>
